Prehistory refers to the period of human existence before written records were kept. Spanning from the emergence of the first humans approximately 6-8 million years ago to the advent of writing, around 5,200 years ago, this era is characterized by the development of complex societies, technologies, and cultural practices. Through archaeology, researchers are able to reconstruct the lives of prehistoric people, analyzing artifacts, architecture, and other remnants of their daily lives. Examples of prehistoric cultures include the Neanderthals, who controlled fire and developed basic tools, and the ancient civilizations of Mesopotamia, which pioneered irrigation and writing. Studying prehistory provides invaluable insights into human evolution, societal development, and the gradual emergence
